  "_notes": "Keyed by a short operator code (your own convention — GWR, AWC, etc). 2026-07-13: seeded 28 new entries from api/incidents.js's TOC_REGION_TABLE, using that table's own 2-letter ATOC-style codes (VT, GR, XC, ...) as the key — name only, awaiting Wikipedia/manual enrichment like any other entry. KNOWN INCONSISTENCY, needs manual review: WMR (West Midlands Railway) predates that seed and uses a different, longer code; TOC_REGION_TABLE's own code for the same operator is WM. Left as two different conventions on purpose rather than silently renaming/merging WMR — do not add a WM entry without first deciding how to reconcile it with WMR. fleet_classes store the EXACT display label as it should appear (not a bare number + assumed 'Class ' prefix) — this covers cases like Manchester Metrolink's M5000 that don't follow the 'Class NN' pattern. 'id' is used to link through to that vehicle's entry on the database page; 'display' is shown verbatim, no reformatting. franchises is the full history; sidebar should show the current one as a simple 'Operating since {start}' line by default, with the full array available as an expandable detail. FIELD OWNERSHIP (see scripts/ for the population scripts): headline/parent_company/franchises are written by scripts/fetch-wikipedia-facts.mjs (Wikipedia, narrative/historical — Claude extracts, never invents; headline is a punchy 8-12 word sentence, not a paragraph; a franchise entry only appears if the article states its dates). schema_jsonld is written by scripts/build-schema-jsonld.mjs (template assembly from the fields above, no new facts, no API calls). stations_operated/regions_served/fleet_classes are manual/curated only — neither OSM nor Wikipedia reliably has these without real risk of being wrong, so they're deliberately not automated. name/wikipedia_title are manual/curated only. _wikipedia is provenance metadata written by the Wikipedia script (no _osm block here — OSM doesn't own any operator-level field in this design; the OSM-derived operator name lives on the station/route entries that reference it, via their own operator/operators fields).",
